{"cursor":"46870","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox disease\n| Name = Eczema Image = dermatitis.jpg Caption = Typical, mild dermatitis\n|\n| ICD10 = - ICD9 = ICDO = OMIM = 603165 MedlinePlus = 000853 eMedicineSubj =\n| Derm eMedicineTopic = 38 eMedicine_mult = MeshID = D004485\n}}  from á¼ÎºÎ¶Î­-ÎµÎ¹Î½ ekzÃ©-ein,  from á¼Îº ek \"out\" + Î¶Î­-ÎµÎ¹Î½ zÃ©-ein\n\"to boil\" |source=(OED)}}\n\n'Eczema' or '[[atopic dermatitis]]' (from Greek\ná¼ÎºÎ¶ÎµÎ¼Î± Äkzema, \"to boil over\") is a form of dermatitis, or\ninflammation of the epidermis (the outer layer of the skin).\n\nThe term eczema is broadly applied to a range of persistent skin conditions.\nThese include dryness and recurring skin rashes that are characterized by one\nor more of these symptoms: redness, skin edema (swelling), itching and dryness,\ncrusting, flaking, blistering, cracking, oozing, or bleeding. Areas of\ntemporary skin discoloration may appear and are sometimes due to healed\ninjuries. Scratching open a healing lesion may result in scarring and may\nenlarge the rash.\n\nThe word eczema comes from Greek, meaning \"to boil over\". Dermatitis comes\nfrom the Greek word for skinand both terms refer to the same skin condition.\nIn some languages, dermatitis and eczema are synonymous, while in other\nlanguages dermatitis implies an acute condition and \"eczema\" a chronic\none. The two conditions are often\nclassified together.\n","linknr":815,"url":"Eczema","recorded":1362503101,"links":65,"instances":["medical","fruit","biology","medicine","medicine","skin","food","psychology"],"pdf":["http://www.astellas.us/docs/protopic.pdf","http://www.astellas.us/docs/protopic.pdf"],"categories":["Autoimmune diseases","Eczema|"],"headings":["Classification","Cause","Diagnosis","Prevention","Treatment","Epidemiology","Research","References","External links",""],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/Mergefrom.svg/50px-Mergefrom.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/w